AB  - Presents 9 experimental studies on auditory discrimination in very young infants, using procedures involving infant control of stimulus duration and habituation of visual attending behavior. Results show that (a) infants at 5 and 6 wks of age showed response decrement of looking at a repeated checkerboard stimulus; (b) when music was added without changing the visual stimulus looking behavior was recovered; (c) beginning at 8 wks of age, visual attention to unchanging visual stimuli declined over weeks but could be recovered by adding the sound of the mother's voice presented via tape recording; (d) addition of the tape-recorded voices of infants' mothers and of a stranger were equally successful in recovering visual attention to unchanging checkerboard stimuli in 8-wk-old infants, and at 9 wks these same infants appeared able to discriminate the 2 different voices; (e) infants at 8 and 9 wks of age could discriminate tone-quality differences in the same voice and could discriminate verbal-content differences; and (f) when slides of the infants' mothers' faces and that of a stranger were unaccompanied by their voices, discrimination was not demonstrated among 10- and 11-wk infants, but when the voices were present there was discrimination. Implications for understanding habituation, cross-modal stimulation, receptive language development, and individual differences are discussed. Appendices concerned with data on looking durations to varying checkerboard stimuli and with the operation of an infant-research laboratory are included. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2021 APA, all rights reserved)
