AB  - 100 1st graders, predominantly low socioeconomic blacks, randomly selected from a suburban public school, were pretested on conservation of 4 physical properties and conservation of melody. Of the 75 who were found to be nonconservers, 60 were trained in 3 20-min sessions by either successive approximation only or by successive approximation plus verbal rule instruction. Both experimental procedures produced a significant number of posttest conservers on the melody training and melody transfer tasks. There was also significant transfer of training in mass, weight, and number by the successive-approximation-only group. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2022 APA, all rights reserved)
